04211nam a22006855i 9780226399294DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263992947 a10.7208/97802263992942doi  a(DE-B1597)523958  a(OCoLC)963935714  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBF378.S65bB366 2017 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a128.3223  aNB 34002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/124082:1 aBarash, Jeffrey Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCollective Memory and the Historical Past /cJeffrey Andrew Barash. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b15 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Sources of Memory -- tPart 1. Symbolic Embodiment, Imagination, and the "Place" of Collective Memory -- tPart 2. Time, Collective Memory, and the Historical Past -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is one critical way we honor great tragedies: by never forgetting. Collective remembrance is as old as human society itself, serving as an important source of social cohesion, yet as Jeffrey Andrew Barash shows in this book, it has served novel roles in a modern era otherwise characterized by discontinuity and dislocation. Drawing on recent theoretical explorations of collective memory, he elaborates an important new philosophical basis for it, one that unveils important limitations to its scope in relation to the historical past. Crucial to Barash's analysis is a look at the radical transformations that the symbolic configurations of collective memory have undergone with the rise of new technologies of mass communication. He provocatively demonstrates how such technologies' capacity to simulate direct experience-especially via the image-actually makes more palpable collective memory's limitations and the opacity of the historical past, which always lies beyond the reach of living memory. Thwarting skepticism, however, he eventually looks to literature-specifically writers such as Marcel Proust, Walter Scott, and W. G. Sebald-to uncover subtle nuances of temporality that might offer inconspicuous emblems of a past historical reality.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCollective memoryxPhilosophy. 0aCollective memory. 0aMemoryxSocial aspects. 4aMarcel Proust. 4aWalter Scott. 4acollective memory. 4ahabitus. 4ahistorical skepticism. 4ahistorical time. 4amass media. 4asymbolic configuration. 4avisual arts. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226399294423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226399294.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles